{{For|the video game developer|Hangar 13 (company)}}
'''Hangar 13''' was a Scottish hardcore [[rave]] venue in [[Ayr]], [[Scotland]]. Situated in the former Pavilion dance hall situated on Ayr's Low Green.  During the early 1990s, raves situated at this old Pavilion became the target of much [[police]] and [[Mass media|media]] interest after three alleged [[Ecstasy (drug)|ecstasy-related]] deaths occurred.<ref name="parliament">{{cite web | url = https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199596/cmhansrd/vo960501/debtext/60501-44.htm | title = Licensing (Amendment)(Scotland) ACT 1996 | work = Hansard | publisher = UK Parliament | date = 1 May 1996}}</ref>

The club was eventually shut down, although there was a "unity campaign" to keep the venue open. The deaths may have been due to the use of more dangerous [[dance drug]]s such as [[para-Methoxyamphetamine|PMA]] rather than [[Methylenedioxymethamphetamine|MDMA]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.obsolete.com/ecstasy/scotland.html | title=Raving in Scotland | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070722222225/http://www.obsolete.com/ecstasy/scotland.html | archivedate=22 July 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>  Other factors included overheating, lack of drinking water and other amenities at these often ''ad hoc'', unlicensed events. The tragic events that happened at Hangar 13 precipitated an amendment to the [[Licensing (Amendment) (Scotland) Act 1996|law]] that licences were required for the safeguarding of the health and safety of those attending similar events.<ref name="misuse">{{cite web | url = http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/research/pdf_res_notes/rn00-106.pdf | title = National Alcohol Misuse Strategy | work = Research Notes | publisher = Scottish Parliament | pages = 4 | date = 4 December 2000 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061026204936/http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/research/pdf_res_notes/rn00-106.pdf | archivedate = 26 October 2006 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>

